Partition by: independent windows per group.

Partition by splits the rows into independent windows, one per distinct value of the partition expression. Each row only sees the rows in its own partition.

The shape of the result is identical to group-by partition logic, but no rows are collapsed. Every input row still appears, with the partition's aggregate attached. This is the workhorse pattern: each detail row sitting alongside its own group total or average.

The mental model to keep is short: group by collapses; over partition by preserves.

The example partitions by customer id, so each order sees only its own customer's rows. It returns each order alongside that customer's total, and the order's percentage of that total, computed as one hundred times the amount divided by the per-customer sum. Every order stays, with its group total attached.
